Task135
When you want to present one person to another, you can use the phrase Let me introduce you to [name]
(name being the person's name). For example, Let me introduce you to Daniel.
Transcript:
Sophie: Brain, let me introduce you to Tom. Tom, this is Brain. He's web developer.

Task136
This is [name] is used to present someone in a conversation. Name refers to a person's name. It's a simple and
direct way to make introductions. For example:

Daniel, this is carol. - HEre, you are telling Daniel about Carol and helping Daniel to know who Carol is.
Transcript:
Sophie: Brain, let me introduce you to Tom. Tom, this is Brain. He's a web developer.

Task137
He is a pronoun used to refer to a male person. Pronouns are useful to avoid repetition and make sentences clearer.
Notice this part of the dialogue:

Tom, this is Brain. He's a web developer. Brain, this is Tom. He's our new graphic designer and he is from Texas,

In the dialogue, after introducing Brain, Sophie uses he to talk about Brain's job. Later, she uses he again
to talk about Tom and his job.

By using he, Sophie doesn't have to repeat the names Brain and Tom. This is the power of the pronouns.
Transcript:
Sophie: Brain, let me introduce you to Tom, this is Brain. He's a web developer.
Sophie: Brain, this is Tom. He's our new graphic designer and he is from Texas.

